review:
I've played the original Overwatch extensively and watched it slowly fall from grace, and have seen just about everything this "sequel" has to offer, so I'm confident in my verdict when I say that Overwatch 2 is a failure as a sequel, a failure as a live service, and a failure as a product.

- Awful monetization that carries on the awful tradition of free-to-play games having "micro"transactions the price of indie games and has somehow convinced the playerbase that lootboxes were better;
- Awful battle pass that uses an egregious Eastern mobile game model that straight-up refuses to let you earn the pass as part of its rewards, as opposed to the one that was spearheaded by Fortnite and every Western battle pass ever since has used;
- Lack of meaningful changes that improves the experience from the first Overwatch, or otherwise awful changes that made the experience WORSE;
- And way more that others before me have already mentioned and aired their grievances atâ€”I'm not in the mood to retread old ground further at this point.

There was a promise of a meaningful sequel dangled, teased, and hyped to all of us, and especially to the people who were burned out by what Overwatch became. The sequel was a lie. All we have is a more imbalanced, less polished, and less fun game, with a change to its monetization model that ended up being worse. And don't get me started on the betrayal of the PvE promise...

...I don't want to say any more. Others have said what I would have wanted to say anyway, including everything here. As a person who had pre-ordered the Origins Edition of the first game and wanted the game to return to form, all I have left are frustration and fatigueâ€”and I'm letting them out now because I know apathy will then follow. Apathy is what this game ultimately deserves.

What a waste of a new universe that once held boundless potential. The world needs heroes more than ever, but not like this.
